resources.description: The About resource is explicitly an Ethos EEDM resource and not granted the same way that Ellucian Business Process APIs are granted.

resources.name: Check Messages Available
resources.description:
A subscribing application may send a HEAD request to see if there are any messages available in the queue. The number of messages available will be returned in a x-remaining header.

|**REST API Specification**	|**Value**|
|-----|-----|
|Method:	|HEAD|
|Route:	|https://integrate.elluciancloud.com/consume|
|Headers:	|Authorization - "Bearer ```<access token>```"|
|Query Parameters:	|lastProcessedID (optional)|

Response
---
- Headers: x-remaining

resources.name: Retrieve Messages
resources.description:
A subscribing application will send a GET request to the API to retrieve messages.

The response is limited by both number of messages and total size (MB):
- The GET request can optionally include a ‘limit’ query parameter that defines the maximum number of messages to retrieve. If the limit parameter is specified (maximum of 1000), the Message Queue API will send up to that number of messages, if available. If the limit parameter is not specified, the Message Queue API will send up to the default limit of 20 messages, if available.
- The total size of the response is limited to 10 MB. If the size limit is reached, the number of messages will be less than the specified number limit.

If there are no messages available, an empty array will be returned.

The subscribing application can optionally send a lastProcessedID query parameter to indicate the ID of the last message it processed. You can use this parameter to retrieve messages that have already been retrieved. The messages in the queue have sequential ID's, and the lastProcessedID parameter corresponds to the ID of a message in the queue. If the application retrieves messages 1-10, but only successfully processes messages 1-5, it can set lastProcessedID=5 in the next request. That will give the application messages 6-10 again. If a lastProcessedID parameter is not included, then previously retrieved messages will be removed from the queue on the next request, and only new messages will be returned.

> Note: Including the lastProcessedID parameter only allows an application to re-retrieve messages from the immediately prior request. After another request is made, all the previously retrieved messages are removed from the queue. For example, If an application retrieves messages 1-20 with one request, then it retrieves messages 21-40 with a second request. If it makes a third request with the parameter lastProcessedID=10, it will get back messages 21-40 again because messages 1-20 were removed from the queue after the second request was made.

It is recommended for a subscribing application to persist the ID of the last message it processed. That way, if the application dies, it will know the last message that was processed when it restarts. The application can then enter that ID into the lastProcessedID parameter to make sure that any messages that were retrieved but not processed are pulled down again. This helps ensure that no messages are missed. If an application does not know where it left off, it can enter lastProcessedID=0, which will return all the previously retrieved messages that are still in the queue. This can result in the application processing some messages twice.

There will also be a x-remaining header in the response indicating how many more messages are in the queue waiting to be retrieved. This does not include the ones in the current response. If there more than 50,000 messages in the queue, the x-remaining header is estimated.

|**REST API Specification**|**Value**|
|---|---|
|Method:	|GET|
|Route:	|https://integrate.elluciancloud.com/consume|
|Headers:	|Authorization - "Bearer ```<access token>```"|
|Query Parameters:	|lastProcessedID (optional)|
|limit |(optional)|

Response
-----
- Headers: x-remaining
- Payload: A JSON array of change-notifications.
